Anaphylaxis: An acute allergic reaction characterized by hives, angioedema, hypotension, and potentially respiratory distress. Requires immediate medical attention.
Urticaria (Hives): Raised, itchy welts on the skin caused by an allergic reaction or other triggers. Can be acute or chronic.
Angioedema: Swelling beneath the skin, often around the face, lips, and throat. Can be a symptom of an allergic reaction.
Hypotension: Low blood pressure, which can cause dizziness, lightheadedness, and fainting.
Serum sickness: An immune complex-mediated hypersensitivity reaction to foreign proteins, often medications. Symptoms include fever, rash, joint pain, and kidney problems.
Mastocytosis: A rare disorder characterized by an abnormal buildup of mast cells in the body, leading to allergic-like symptoms.
Vasculitis: Inflammation of blood vessels, which can cause a variety of symptoms including skin rash, joint pain, and organ damage.
Hereditary Angioedema: A rare genetic disorder characterized by recurrent episodes of swelling of the skin and mucous membranes.
Toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN): A rare and serious skin reaction that can be life-threatening. Symptoms include widespread blistering and peeling of the skin.

Stevens-Johnson syndrome (SJS): A serious skin reaction that is less severe than TEN but can still be life-threatening. Symptoms include blistering and peeling of the skin, fever, and internal organ involvement.
